-- Sub-Saharan African Stocks: First Bank, MCB, Safaricom, UBA, Zenith Bank
-- B y   V i n c e n t   N w a n m a   a n d   J o h n s t o n e   T u r a n a
-- 2010-11-09T16:05:43Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-11-09/sub-saharan-african-stocks-first-bank-mcb-safaricom-uba-zenith-bank.html
The  Nigerian Stock Exchange All-Share
Index  surged to the highest in three months, adding 2.6 percent
to 25,383.37 by the 1 p.m. close in Lagos, according to an e-
mailed statement from the exchange.  Mauritius’s  SEMDEX Index  gained for a second day, rising 1
percent to 1,890.15 by the 1:30 p.m. close in Port Louis, while
Kenya’s  All-Share Index  retreated 0.9 percent to 84.18 by the 3
p.m. close in Nairobi. Namibia’s  FTSE/Namibia Overall Index 
climbed for the fourth time in five days, increasing 0.5 percent
to 853.60 by 5 p.m. in Windhoek.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan Africa,
excluding South Africa. Stock symbols are in parentheses.  Mauritius Commercial Bank  (MCB MP), the Indian Ocean island
nation’s biggest lender by market value, climbed 2 rupees, or
1.4 percent, to 150 rupees, the highest in more than a year. The
lender that makes up more than 22 percent of Mauritius’s SEMDEX
Index rose on speculation it will maintain its interim dividend
at last year’s level.  “We would expect the banking group to maintain its interim
dividend at 2.25 rupees per share,” Kishen Nadassen, senior
research analyst at Port Louis-based Cim Stockbrokers Ltd., said
in a phone interview from the city. The dividend declaration
will coincide with the publication of the bank’s first-quarter
results that are due at the end of the week, he said.  Safaricom Ltd.  (SAFCOM KN), Kenya’s biggest mobile-phone
operator, rose for a second day, adding 5 cents, or 1.1 percent,
to 4.75 shillings, the highest since Nov. 4, on expectations
that first-half profit will grow, said  Eric Musau , an analyst at
African Alliance Securities Ltd. Safaricom will announce
earnings for the six months through September tomorrow.  “We expect the converged communication-solutions provider
to release a robust set of results and set a strong guidance
for” the full year, Musau said in a phone interview from
Nairobi. Annual profit may increase 19 percent, he said.  Zenith Bank Plc  (ZENITHBA NL), Nigeria’s biggest lender by
market value, climbed 68 kobo, or 4.9 percent, to 14.67 naira,
the highest since May 21. Nigeria will buy 2.2 trillion naira
($14.6 billion) of bad debts from banks by the end of the year,
the central bank said in an e-mailed statement, raising its
previous forecast.  First Bank of Nigeria Plc  (FIRSTBAN NL), the
second-largest, added the most since Oct. 18, rallying 60 kobo,
or 4.9 percent, to 12.76 naira.  United Bank for Africa Plc  (UBA
NL) gained the most in more than a month, surging 44 kobo, or
4.9 percent, to 9.39 naira.  To contact the reporters on this story:
